    "summary": "CSS architecture readiness for GTD design evolution",
    "content": "Hey Steve, Lea here. I've been looking at the CSS architecture in preparation for the GTD evolution. A few things I wanted to flag from a design perspective:\n\n1. **Layout shift**: Our current design is a single narrow column (40rem max). GTD typically needs a sidebar navigation to switch between Inbox, Next Actions, Projects, etc. Have you been thinking about a two-panel layout? I'm imagining something like a collapsible sidebar on desktop that becomes a top-level nav or hamburger on mobile.\n\n2. **New token needs**: We might need additional design tokens as the UI grows -- things like sidebar widths, icon sizes, badge/tag colors for contexts (@phone, @computer, etc.). The current token system is solid but scoped to a simpler app.\n\n3. **Component reuse**: The current `.todo-item` component is versatile. For GTD, items in different lists (Inbox vs Next Actions vs Waiting For) will likely share the same base structure but with different metadata visible. I'm thinking a base item component with modifier classes rather than separate component styles for each list type.\n\n4. **Steve Schoger flagged gaps last time**: `todo-add__error`, `nav-logout`, `auth-form__message :empty`, and `auth-form__cancel` had missing or incomplete styles. We addressed some of those but might want to audit the full CSS before adding more components.\n\nWhat's your vision for the visual evolution? I want to make sure our CSS architecture supports whatever design direction you're imagining."
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to carson-gross's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "lea-verou",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@carson-gross",
    "targetColor": "orange",
    "summary": "HTMX patterns for GTD multi-view navigation",
    "content": "Hey Carson, Lea here. As we think about the GTD evolution, I wanted to share some frontend thoughts specifically around HTMX patterns since this directly affects how we structure the HTML and CSS.

The GTD system has distinct views: Inbox, Next Actions (filterable by Context), Projects, Waiting For, Someday/Maybe, and a Weekly Review flow. Here's how I see the HTMX architecture working:

**Navigation Pattern**: A sidebar nav with links to each GTD view. On click, HTMX swaps just the main content area. This keeps the sidebar persistent and avoids full page reloads. The sidebar stays in the `<nav>` landmark, and the main content swaps within `<main>`.

```html
<nav class="gtd-sidebar" aria-label="GTD views">
  <a href="/inbox" hx-get="/inbox" hx-target="#gtd-content" hx-push-url="true">Inbox</a>
  <a href="/next-actions" hx-get="/next-actions" hx-target="#gtd-content" hx-push-url="true">Next Actions</a>
  <!-- etc -->
</nav>
<main id="gtd-content">
  <!-- swapped content -->
</main>
```

**Processing Inbox Items**: The "clarify" step is essentially a decision tree -- "Is it actionable?" -> if yes, "2 minutes or less?" -> if no, "Delegate or do myself?" -> assign to Next Actions or Waiting For. This could work as a series of HTMX-driven form steps within a single item, or as a modal/panel that slides in. Each decision replaces the current step with the next question.

**Context Filtering**: Next Actions filtered by @context tags could use HTMX with URL params: `hx-get="/next-actions?context=phone"`. The filter UI stays, the list content swaps.

**Key CSS implication**: We need a two-panel layout (sidebar + content) that collapses responsively. CSS Grid is perfect for this:
```css
.gtd-layout {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr;  /* mobile: single column */
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .gtd-layout {
    grid-template-columns: 16rem 1fr;  /* desktop: sidebar + content */
  }
}
```

What are your thoughts on the HTMX patterns here? Any concerns about the navigation-via-swap approach vs. full page loads?"
  }
}
